					<h4>Western Book Roundup</h4>
		
		<h1>Regional Bookstores Feature a Doctor and Two Colorado Gottliebs</h1>
		<h2><i></i></h2>
		<div class="text-feature_print">
							<p>By Jenny Shank, 1-16-08</p>
			
							<table width="25" align="right" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">
					<tr>
						<td>&nbsp;</td>
						<td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/thumbnails_feature/thiscommonsecret_thumb.gif" align="right" width="98" height="150" /></td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/spacer.gif" width="1" height="3" border="0" /></td></tr>

					
					<tr><td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/spacer.gif" width="1" height="3" border="0" /></td></tr>
				</table>
			
							<p>Regional bookstores are packing their schedules with events again after a holiday lull, and several local authors will be presenting their books this week. 
</p>
<p>
Bozeman writer Alan Kesselheim and Susan Wicklund will read from their new book, <I><a target="_blank" href="http://www.amazon.com/This-Common-Secret-Journey-Abortion/dp/158648480X/ref=pd_bbs_sr_1?ie=UTF8&amp;s=books&amp;qid=1200368523&amp;sr=8-1" title="This Common Secret: My Journey As An Abortion Doctor">This Common Secret: My Journey As An Abortion Doctor</a></I> at Bozeman&#8217;s The Country Bookshelf on Thursday, January 17 (7 p.m.).&nbsp; The book discusses Wicklund&#8217;s medical career, which &#8220;requires her to wear a bulletproof vest and to carry a .38 caliber revolver,&#8221; and tells the stories of women who have had abortions.&nbsp; Wicklund <a target="_blank" href="http://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/06/health/06abor.html?_r=1&amp;oref=slogin" title="told the New York Times">told the New York Times</a>, &#8220;Because it is such a secret, we lose sight of how common it is.&#8221;  They will swing back through Montana in February, reading at Missoula&#8217;s <a target="_blank" href="http://www.factandfictionbooks.com/NASApp/store/IndexJsp" title="Fact &amp; Fiction">Fact &amp; Fiction</a> on the 21st.
</p>
<p>
On Sunday, January 20, the Boulder Bookstore is hosting the panel, <a target="_blank" href="http://boulderbookstore.booksense.com/NASApp/store/IndexJsp?s=storeevents&amp;eventId=364581" title=""So, You Want to Write A Book"">&#8220;So, You Want to Write A Book&#8221;</a> (3 p.m.). Denver literary agent Kristin Nelson (who <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/an_interview_with_denver_literary_agent_kristin_nelson/C131/L39/" title="spoke to NewWest.Net/books">spoke to NewWest.Net/books</a> last year), local authors Kim Reid and Michelle Dally, Jennifer Coffee, acquisitions editor at <a target="_blank" href="http://www.soundstrue.com/" title="Sounds True Publishing">Sounds True Publishing</a> in Boulder, and Bella Stander, a &#8220;promotional consultant,&#8221; will share their book writing, publishing, and marketing tips.
</p>
<p>
And this month brings the publication of books by two Colorado writers named Gottlieb.&nbsp; Former Denver Post reporter <a target="_blank" href="http://www.authoralangottlieb.com/" title="Alan Gottleib">Alan Gottleib</a> just published his novel <I><a target="_blank" href="http://www.amazon.com/Ultimate-Excursions-Alan-Gottlieb/dp/0977418820/ref=pd_bbs_sr_1?ie=UTF8&amp;s=books&amp;qid=1200367338&amp;sr=8-1" title="Ultimate Excursions">Ultimate Excursions</a></I> (Paandaa), a thriller set in Peru.&nbsp; According to <a target="_blank" href="http://www.denverpost.com/husted" title="Bill Husted">Bill Husted</a>, the gossip columnist for the Denver Post: &#8220;The main character in the book is Tim Lake, a newspaperman at the Denver Banner.&nbsp; And the paper&#8217;s editor acts and sounds a lot like former Post editor Gil Spencer.&#8221; Alan Gottlieb will read from his book at the Glendale Barnes &amp; Noble on February 2 (1 p.m.).
</p>
<p>
Meanwhile, Boulder writer Eli Gottlieb&#8217;s new literary thriller, <I><a target="_blank" href="http://www.amazon.com/Now-You-See-Him-Novel/dp/0061284645/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&amp;s=books&amp;qid=1200367672&amp;sr=1-1" title="Now You See Him">Now You See Him</a></I> (William Morrow) will hit bookstores on January 22.&nbsp; <a target="_blank" href="http://search.barnesandnoble.com/booksearch/isbnInquiry.asp?z=y&amp;EAN=9780061284649&amp;itm=1" title="Kirkus Reviews">Kirkus Reviews</a> describes the book as being about &#8220;a midlife crisis in upstate New York.&#8221;  Eli Gottlieb will present his book February 5 at the <a target="_blank" href="http://boulderbookstore.booksense.com/NASApp/store/IndexJsp?s=storeevents&amp;eventId=364590" title="Boulder Bookstore">Boulder Bookstore</a> (7:30 p.m.).&nbsp; Gottlieb is a contributing editor to 5280 Magazine, which offers <a target="_blank" href="http://www.5280.com/issues/2007/0712/feature.php?pageID=954" title="an excerpt from the book here">an excerpt from the book here</a>.
</p>
<p>
Have some regional literary news or events to share?&nbsp; If so,  <script type="text/javascript">
